events.name: Women Techmakers Tucson Hackathon

venue.name: University of Arizona: Science and Engineering Library:

events.description:
Google Development Group, Code for Tucson, and UA Libraries are proud to present the Women Techmakers Tucson Hackathon on November 14-15 at the University of Arizona's Science and Engineering Library.

Join us for a weekend of food, fun, learning, and hacking! This free event provides an opportunity for women of all levels of technical expertise to collaboratively develop tech-driven projects over the course of two days. All women are encouraged to attend--no computer programming experience required!

Click here for the event schedule: http://tinyurl.com/p43dq5d

Event highlights:

• Workshops on coding, rapid prototyping (e.g. electronic circuit building and 3D printing), and professional development

• Mentoring and on-site tech support during project development

• Professional development opportunities and community partnership occasions

• Childcare provided during workshops (please email [masked] for more details)

• Amazing swag, prizes, and food

Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs):

What is a hackathon?

An event for women of all different technical expertise to come together to develop awesome tech-driven projects over a short time period.

“Hacking” sounds illegal/shady?

Definitely not! Well, this kind of hacking is not. This hackathon provides the space for women to collaborate and work on ideas together.

Is it going to cost me a fortune to attend?

The entire event is free!

Do I need extensive hacking/tech skills to participate?

Not at all! Women of all technical expertise and levels are encouraged to attend. No programming experience needed.

I see that your event has workshops... Do those cost extra to attend?

They are free! Workshops are available free of cost to registered attendees. Workshop topics cover a variety of tech-related topics, and are led by super-talented women too!

Why the asterisk on women?

The word “women” can seem exclusive and alienating to some. We use the asterisk to include anyone who identifies as cis-women, trans*, intersex and queer people who identify as women.

Do I need to bring anything?

A laptop is recommended. Don’t have one? No worries! Just bring your awesome self.

Do you provide childcare?

Yes, we do! We provide childcare during the workshops portion of the event from 9:15-2:15.

Do I have to stay all day on both days?

Nope! Stay as long as you like, and come and go as you please.

Will there be prizes?

Heck yeah! Prizes in several categories, too (again, you don't *have* to be a coder to participate).

So... do you think I should attend?

Heck yes! This is a great opportunity to network and collaborate with women techies of all levels. Also, this is your chance to bring your cool app idea, website idea, or product idea to life.

I can’t contain myself. How do I sign up?

I thought you’d ask! Register on this Meetup page. :)

What happens if I have more questions?

Direct your questions to [masked] !

events.description:
Join us the last Monday of every month from 5:30 - 7:30 PM for introductory sessions about tools and technologies to make your business more successful...or to start your own business.

The topic this month will be Creating an online presence with Google Domains.

We'll talk about why you might want to create an online presence, how to secure a domain, how to create a web page or blog, and creating an email for your new domain. While the focus will be on Google Domains, alternatives from Wordpress to GitHub will also be discussed.

events.name: Tucson Study Jam! (Biz Tech Special Sessions)
events.description:
Join us in the Idea+Space every Monday for a special Biz Tech session of the Google Developers Study Jam. This week we will review the material from Lesson 2A: Making An App Interactive.

Here's some additional information about Study Jams and the course:

Study Jams are community-organized study groups around Google online developer courses. The goal is to support as many students as possible in completing the course, thereby raising the technical level of the community.

The Study Jam for Android Development for Beginners is best suited for two audiences: 1) those new to programming 2) those with programming experience who have never used Android.

You can enroll in the course here:
https://www.udacity.com/account/affiliate/GoogleStudyJams

What you will get:
- Personal tutoring on the course material
- Community setting to support course learning
- Swag pack
- Google-offered Study Jams completion certificate
- Discount on the Android Nanodegree upon course completion
- Opportunity to join Google Launchpad with completed app, pending app quality

So, come join us for the Study Jam!﻿

Join us for a weekend of food, fun, learning, and hacking! This free event provides an opportunity for women of all levels of technical expertise to collaboratively develop tech-driven projects over the course of two days. events.description:
Bring a lunch and learn about emerging technologies that could be helpful for your business...or an opportunity for a new business!

This month we will be using the Google Big Query tool to visualize some of the data from the recently completed election. Topics covered will include ways to visualize data, data sources, and visualizing Big Data with Big Query. Then you'll get a chance to explore campaign finance data using Big Query - so bring a laptop! (If you don't have one, there will be some laptops available.)

events.name: Biz Tech Brown Bag Session: Design Sprints
events.description: Design matters. Speed matters. What if we could have both? A design sprint is a five-phase framework that helps answer critical business questions through rapid prototyping and user testing. Sprints let your team reach clearly defined goals and deliverables and gain key learnings, quickly. The process helps spark innovation, encourage user-centered thinking, align your team under a shared vision, and get you to product launch faster.

This is a chance to get a professional accreditation that demonstrates you have an understanding of basic and advanced aspects of mobile website design and development. By learning together we think it’s going to be more fun and more of us are going to be able to complete it.

Android projects: Android water bottle
AR/VR projects: Google Daydream headset
Assistant projects: Google Home Mini
ML/IoT projects: Sparkfun Edge development board

Plus ARCore thumb drives or Google notebooks for all team members.
